1
00:00:01,280 --> 00:00:18,275
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:18,695 --> 00:00:27,315
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa.

3
00:00:27,335 --> 00:00:34,610
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:34,792 --> 00:00:41,241
Yesterday I gave the moon talk and then it failed to, well, I failed to do the right thing and so I lost it.

5
00:00:41,762 --> 00:00:43,405
So I'm doing it again.

6
00:00:43,465 --> 00:00:55,460
I'll be covering exactly the same ground, but of course it won't be quite the same as you yourself had heard it, or as those on the moon broadcast had heard it.

7
00:00:56,423 --> 00:01:03,972
So we're talking about the dependent origination and centering towards the end on this process of desiring.

8
00:01:06,028 --> 00:01:17,625
Now, the depeneration begins with this word avidya, and it's been translated as ignorance, giving it some sort of culpability, you know, like we shouldn't have been ignorant.

9
00:01:17,784 --> 00:01:22,031
But no, this is just a plain flat not knowing, didn't know.

10
00:01:22,070 --> 00:01:25,917
And it's because of that that we fall into a delusion.

11
00:01:26,658 --> 00:01:35,310
Now, that delusion, of course, is to believe ourselves to be this heart, body and mind, this psychophysical organism.

12
00:01:35,424 --> 00:02:01,197
that leads us into a funny relationship with the world wanting to be happy so we acquire things money friends power and so on and then anything that upsets us or threatens us we push away we get angry and so on and if it's bigger than me then of course i'll run for it so these are your basic attitudes that come from that delusion

13
00:02:01,867 --> 00:02:03,570
inquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

14
00:02:04,072 --> 00:02:07,076
And they have created these sankara.

15
00:02:07,537 --> 00:02:12,265
The sankara is translated rather awkwardly as volitional conditioning.

16
00:02:12,926 --> 00:02:17,014
But I think it's much easier to think of them just as our habits.

17
00:02:17,574 --> 00:02:22,223
Habits of thought, habits of feeling, habits of reaction and so on.

18
00:02:24,008 --> 00:02:35,145
And these two, this not knowing, this delusion, and the sankara, the habits, underlie every moment of our life.

19
00:02:35,165 --> 00:02:37,711
They're just passing with us underneath every moment.

20
00:02:38,832 --> 00:02:46,405
Now, when something moves on the sankara, it will manifest on that screen of consciousness.

21
00:02:46,655 --> 00:03:02,129
And consciousness is described by its six bases, the five sensual bases, the eye, ear, nose, and so on, and the mind-heart, the inner life of images, thoughts, emotions.

22
00:03:03,591 --> 00:03:13,000
And these five consciousnesses, whenever there's a stimulus, it'll manifest on that screen.

23
00:03:14,937 --> 00:03:26,866
Now then we have, because of that screen, we of course become aware of our body and mind, of our materiality and of our mentality.

24
00:03:27,467 --> 00:03:36,215
And it can also be understood as what is subjective, mentality, and what is objective, our physicality.

25
00:03:37,355 --> 00:03:44,741
And this psychophysical organism has of course these six sense bases.

26
00:03:45,228 --> 00:04:00,501
And whenever we have a contact, which includes a sense base, some sort of object, and the awareness, the consciousness of it, we have that moment when we become aware of something, conscious of something.

27
00:04:02,682 --> 00:04:14,052
Now, that moment is, shall we say, just an experience, but we then put a judgment on it.

28
00:04:14,623 --> 00:04:19,333
or we look at it from the point of view of happiness.

29
00:04:19,733 --> 00:04:24,302
So obviously there are some things that make us happy and some things that don't.

30
00:04:25,163 --> 00:04:29,612
And that's the point where it becomes vedana, or feeling.

31
00:04:29,845 --> 00:04:33,009
physical feelings, mental feelings.

32
00:04:33,069 --> 00:04:46,630
So as soon as these first little sensations come up in our sitting posture, for instance, of pain in the knee or pain in the back or pain in the neck, as soon as they come up, immediately we say, oh, that's pain.

33
00:04:47,091 --> 00:04:48,774
Pain meaning don't like.

34
00:04:50,416 --> 00:04:56,747
And of course, if it's something pleasant, we suddenly have a lovely, joyous memory, then of course,

35
00:04:57,233 --> 00:05:00,661
we label that as something to be enjoyed.

36
00:05:02,384 --> 00:05:06,673
It's the point next which is the problem, how we relate to it.

37
00:05:07,274 --> 00:05:09,420
And this is our reactivity.

38
00:05:10,413 --> 00:05:22,461
So because we've determined to try to make this life really absolutely happy, whenever something does create happiness, we grasp it, we try to maintain it, we try to make it grow.

39
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:27,492
And when something is unpleasant, we want to push it away, etc.

40
00:05:28,401 --> 00:05:35,567
That's the point of this tanha, this translated as craving, but that's too strong.

41
00:05:35,767 --> 00:05:44,696
Thirst is not bad, but it's just that reactivity coming from the wrong understanding.

42
00:05:44,716 --> 00:05:47,639
Now, at the next point, there's an identity.

43
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:54,343
And this is the point where actually suffering begins, because that's when you say, this is me.

44
00:05:54,685 --> 00:05:56,887
I am this pain in the knee.

45
00:05:57,286 --> 00:05:58,408
I am depressed.

46
00:05:59,653 --> 00:06:07,824
And once that is determined, it's virtually impossible to stop the empowerment of that desire.

47
00:06:08,968 --> 00:06:21,480
So if the desire said, take an aspirin, get rid of this headache, and you say, yes, I will take an aspirin to get rid of it, it's virtually impossible to stop reaching out for the aspirin.

48
00:06:21,841 --> 00:06:29,749
You may, of course, change your mind in the process, but the reaching out or the movement towards, even the slightest movement, will be very difficult to stop.

49
00:06:31,451 --> 00:06:38,216
And then once you've started an action, there'll be a process of the action and the completion of the action, right?

50
00:06:38,668 --> 00:06:45,918
Now that's looking at dependent origination from a present moment-to-moment experience.

51
00:06:45,937 --> 00:06:50,723
But of course it is also explained as a sort of three lives.

52
00:06:51,725 --> 00:07:04,120
In the past life we develop these habits, we come into this life with consciousness, with awareness, we go through this process, we build up hopefully better

53
00:07:04,387 --> 00:07:12,019
habits which get us reborn in a better place and life begins again, birth, death, birth, death.

54
00:07:12,379 --> 00:07:28,824
But to us, I think, as, well, what can we say, as Westerners, really much more involved in our psychology and all that, then the moment-to-moment

55
00:07:29,682 --> 00:07:36,454
the present moment experience of Dependent Origination makes much more sense to us.

56
00:07:36,473 --> 00:07:44,569
Now this is what's really important here is the Buddha's tremendous insight about the point of

57
00:07:45,324 --> 00:08:11,586
in identity so if we take a very simple sentence which some of you will have heard me often use one sees ice cream one makes a contact with ice cream it's a lovely sunny day it's very warm you're out walking and there it is the vision the seeing of the ice cream and immediately that brings up a sense of liking

58
00:08:11,565 --> 00:08:15,629
Once you like something, there's a wanting, right?

59
00:08:15,649 --> 00:08:18,072
So there's a contact, I scream.

60
00:08:18,774 --> 00:08:21,295
There's like, I scream.

61
00:08:21,656 --> 00:08:23,978
There's want, I scream.

62
00:08:23,999 --> 00:08:27,742
And then there's I want, I scream.

63
00:08:27,762 --> 00:08:30,365
So the I comes in late in the process.

64
00:08:31,346 --> 00:08:33,129
I is a sense of identity.

65
00:08:33,149 --> 00:08:34,289
This is me.

66
00:08:35,091 --> 00:08:38,534
If that weren't so, there wouldn't be an escape.

67
00:08:38,784 --> 00:08:39,927
there wouldn't be an escape.

68
00:08:40,269 --> 00:08:51,039
It's the fact that it comes at the end of that process, that we can now, instead of moving into that identity, actually stop at the point of desire.

69
00:08:52,386 --> 00:08:57,234
And when we stop at the point of desire, we can see that process quite clearly.

70
00:08:57,815 --> 00:09:07,347
It's a sort of energy that wants to manifest, and it needs our permission, a decision to manifest.

71
00:09:07,369 --> 00:09:10,332
And that's what comes after this identity.

72
00:09:10,592 --> 00:09:12,535
It's known as bhava, becoming.

73
00:09:13,037 --> 00:09:17,482
When we are becoming, we are creating a self.

74
00:09:17,462 --> 00:09:22,671
all the time, but it's also an action, and therefore there are consequences.

75
00:09:23,773 --> 00:09:26,538
And it all reverts back to this desire.

76
00:09:26,878 --> 00:09:34,409
Now, we're talking here specifically about unwholesome desire, but it also works for wholesome desires.

77
00:09:34,791 --> 00:09:39,217
Now, unlike the Buddha, we have this underlying

78
00:09:40,429 --> 00:09:43,596
We have this underlying delusion.

79
00:09:43,897 --> 00:09:48,404
And so, no matter how we try, there'll always be that sense of self.

80
00:09:49,187 --> 00:09:57,182
Now, that doesn't mean to say it somehow destroys the benefit of a good action.

81
00:09:57,543 --> 00:09:58,725
Far from it.

82
00:09:58,705 --> 00:10:01,893
But there'll always be that sense of me doing something.

83
00:10:02,475 --> 00:10:14,807
And with it, this underlying little conversation about how wonderful we are or how we're not so wonderful or how we've given too much, spent too much, and so on and so forth.

84
00:10:16,423 --> 00:10:23,591
So now, if we go back to this desire, we have to feel that, okay?

85
00:10:23,630 --> 00:10:34,481
So in our meditation, when we're sitting there, as soon as something comes into our attention, on that screen of consciousness, we become aware of it, right?

86
00:10:34,923 --> 00:10:43,831
As soon as that happens, the Mahasi technique of labeling is extremely good at making us acknowledge what is happening.

87
00:10:44,554 --> 00:10:50,681
So if my mind is wandering, I note wandering, but then I can see that I'm planning something.

88
00:10:50,701 --> 00:10:51,861
So I note planning.

89
00:10:51,922 --> 00:11:01,192
And when I come back into the body, I can feel the agitation, the excitement of this amazing thing that I'm going to do, saving the world.

90
00:11:02,113 --> 00:11:10,461
And if I can stay with that, I'll see that there's a sort of little energy that wants to take me out, take me back into the dream world.

91
00:11:12,128 --> 00:11:13,692
And I've got to be aware of that.

92
00:11:14,332 --> 00:11:21,830
If there's an iota, a moment of inattention, I'll shoot off again up into la-la land.

93
00:11:23,693 --> 00:11:31,250
So this whole process is explained by the Buddha in this dependent origination.

94
00:11:32,091 --> 00:11:45,854
And this desire has to be felt, it has to be known, it has to be understood, so that when a desire comes and we see it is unwholesome, we've got to hold it there, we've got to stand.

95
00:11:46,354 --> 00:11:55,028
We mustn't let it take us, we mustn't let it tempt us into an action of thought, word or deed.

96
00:11:55,226 --> 00:12:11,278
and if we fail that's not a problem you just know that ah yeah it's still a very strong habit so okay i've got to work with it which means the next time it arises being slightly on the ball just waiting for that energy to dissipate dissipate dissipate

97
00:12:11,544 --> 00:12:13,846
Now that energy, remember, doesn't disappear.

98
00:12:14,268 --> 00:12:16,929
It's always transforming to its opposite.

99
00:12:17,009 --> 00:12:20,133
So where there was selfishness, they'll find generosity.

100
00:12:20,653 --> 00:12:22,936
Where there's hatred, you'll find love.

101
00:12:23,296 --> 00:12:28,480
And where there's cruelty, you'll find compassion, and so on.

102
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:32,865
So that was our little contemplation yesterday.

103
00:12:32,924 --> 00:12:40,692
It was probably slightly better, slightly longer yesterday, but at least we have

104
00:12:41,009 --> 00:12:44,504
gone over it again.

105
00:12:45,126 --> 00:12:50,731
So it'll be slightly different from what you heard yesterday, but at least we've covered the same area.

106
00:12:51,217 --> 00:13:06,996
Now, I think I also said, just to finish off, this moment of desire is actually the only moment of, for want of a better word, free will.

107
00:13:07,758 --> 00:13:11,623
That's the point where we can actually say no or yes.

108
00:13:12,042 --> 00:13:18,594
Otherwise, we would just be automatons, we'd just be living faithfully.

109
00:13:18,833 --> 00:13:21,818
We wouldn't have an ability to guide ourselves.

110
00:13:22,640 --> 00:13:34,100
Now, when I say that's the moment of choice, the moment of free will, actually speaking, it's very narrow, because what we want to do is get to a point of liberation from suffering.

111
00:13:34,198 --> 00:13:36,365
And the path is ahead of us.

112
00:13:36,384 --> 00:13:50,722
Now we come along the path as if you were, so we say, just walking in the country, going somewhere, to a tea shop perhaps, of course, to a place where you can get a nice cup of coffee and a tea cake.

113
00:13:50,702 --> 00:14:12,542
and you know the way it's on the map right and as you're going along there's a little road to the left and as you look you think oh that's interesting so now you've got a choice you see you can either wander up there wasting time getting more and more anxious as to whether you the tea shop will be closed by the time you get there and getting all flustered and you may get lost

114
00:14:12,522 --> 00:14:12,923
You see?

115
00:14:12,942 --> 00:14:14,144
Even though you've got a map.

116
00:14:14,885 --> 00:14:18,091
And so you have to decide at that crossroad, have I got time?

117
00:14:18,150 --> 00:14:19,133
Do I want to go there?

118
00:14:19,153 --> 00:14:20,294
Do I need to go there?

119
00:14:20,995 --> 00:14:23,078
And then you move on, right?

120
00:14:24,381 --> 00:14:33,096
So that moment of choice, when the desire comes up, is the point where we can

121
00:14:33,498 --> 00:14:43,628
liberate ourselves, that we can actually make the decisions that will liberate ourselves from this whole process of desire.

122
00:14:45,889 --> 00:15:01,884
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even further confusion, and that you will, by your devotion to practice, liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

123
00:15:05,830 --> 00:15:07,660
I hope you like the photo, by the way.

124
00:15:07,681 --> 00:15:11,081
That's the centre on a very hot, lovely day.

